Path: godot/tutorials/rendering/viewports.rst
Summary: Explains how cameras interact with Viewports and how to control rendering layers.
When using a Camera3D or Camera2D, it will always display on the closest parent Viewport (going towards the root). For example, in the following hierarchy:

CameraA will display on the Root Viewport and it will draw MeshA. CameraB will be captured by the SubViewport along with MeshB. Even though MeshB is in the scene hierarchy, it will still not be drawn to the Root Viewport. Similarly, MeshA will not be visible from the SubViewport because SubViewports only capture nodes below them in the hierarchy.

There can only be one active camera per Viewport, so if there is more than one, make sure that the desired one has the current property set, or make it the current camera by calling:

GDScript:
camera.make_current()

C#:
camera.MakeCurrent();

By default, cameras will render all objects in their world. In 3D, cameras can use their cull_mask property combined with the VisualInstance3D's layer property to restrict which objects are rendered.
---CHUNK---
Document: Viewports
Path: godot/tutorials/rendering/viewports.rst
Summary: This section explains how to control the size and scaling of SubViewport nodes, particularly when they are not children of SubViewportContainers.
SubViewports have a `size` property that defines their resolution in pixels. For SubViewports that are direct children of SubViewportContainers, this `size` property is overridden. However, for other SubViewports, the `size` property directly sets their resolution.

It is also possible to scale the 2D content within a SubViewport and set its resolution independently of the `size` property. This is achieved by using the `set_size_2d_override` method and `set_size_2d_override_stretch` property.

GDScript:
sub_viewport.set_size_2d_override(Vector2i(width, height)) # Custom size for 2D.
sub_viewport.set_size_2d_override_stretch(true) # Enable stretch for custom size.

C#:
subViewport.Size2DOverride = new Vector2I(width, height); # Custom size for 2D.
subViewport.Size2DOverrideStretch = true; # Enable stretch for custom size.

For details on scaling and stretching the Root Viewport, refer to the Multiple Resolutions Tutorial.
---CHUNK---
Document: Viewports
Path: godot/tutorials/rendering/viewports.rst
Summary: Explains how Viewports manage 3D and 2D worlds for rendering and physics.
In 3D, a Viewport contains a World3D, which links physics and rendering. Node3D-based nodes register with the closest Viewport's World3D. By default, new Viewports use their parent's World3D, with the Root Viewport having the primary World3D.

The World3D property of a Viewport can be set to a specific World3D, isolating its child nodes from the parent Viewport's World3D. This is useful for displaying separate 3D elements, like a character overlay.

For instancing single 3D objects without needing a full World3D, Viewports offer the Own World3D property. This is particularly helpful when integrating 3D characters or objects into a World2D context.

In 2D, each Viewport inherently possesses its own World2D. While this is usually sufficient, sharing World2D instances between Viewports is possible by programmatically setting the world_2d property.

Demo projects illustrating these concepts are available for "3D in 2D" and "2D in 3D".
---CHUNK---
Document: Viewports
Path: godot/tutorials/rendering/viewports.rst
Summary: This section explains how to capture the contents of a Viewport as an image and the timing considerations for doing so.

You can capture the contents of a Viewport, which for the root Viewport is equivalent to a screen capture. This is achieved using the `get_image()` method on the Viewport's texture.

GDScript:
```gdscript
# Retrieve the captured Image using get_image().
var img = get_viewport().get_texture().get_image()
# Convert Image to ImageTexture.
var tex = ImageTexture.create_from_image(img)
# Set sprite texture.
sprite.texture = tex
```

C#:
```csharp
// Retrieve the captured Image using get_image().
var img = GetViewport().GetTexture().GetImage();
// Convert Image to ImageTexture.
var tex = ImageTexture.CreateFromImage(img);
// Set sprite texture.
sprite.Texture = tex;
```

Key Rule: If you attempt to capture the Viewport's image in `_ready()` or during the first frame of the Viewport's initialization, you will receive an empty texture because no content has been rendered yet. To avoid this, you must wait until the frame has finished rendering.

GDScript:
```gdscript
# Wait until the frame has finished before getting the texture.
await RenderingServer.frame_post_draw
# You can get the image after this.
```

C#:
```csharp
// Wait until the frame has finished before getting the texture.
await ToSignal(RenderingServer.Singleton, RenderingServer.SignalName.FramePostDraw);
// You can get the image after this.
```
---CHUNK---
