Document: Viewports
Path: godot/tutorials/rendering/viewports.rst
Summary: This section explains how to configure rendering properties for Viewports, including MSAA, disabling 3D rendering, and using Debug Draw modes.

Viewports expose rendering properties that can differ from project settings. You can set a different level of MSAA for each Viewport, with the default being Disabled.

If a Viewport is only used for 2D, you can disable 3D rendering. This is slightly faster and uses less memory.

Note: To render 3D shadows in a Viewport, set the positional_shadow_atlas_size property to a value greater than 0. The default project setting is 4096 for desktop and 2048 for mobile.

Viewports also allow customization of how scenes are drawn using Debug Draw modes. Debug Draw is Disabled by default. Other options include Unshaded, Overdraw, and Wireframe.

- Debug Draw = Disabled (default): The scene is drawn normally.
- Debug Draw = Unshaded: The scene is drawn without lighting, making objects appear flatly colored.
- Debug Draw = Overdraw: Meshes are drawn semi-transparent with an additive blend to visualize overlaps.
- Debug Draw = Wireframe: The scene is drawn using only the edges of triangles in the meshes.

Note: Debug Draw modes are not supported with the Compatibility rendering method and will appear as regular draw modes.
---CHUNK---
Document: Viewports
Path: godot/tutorials/rendering/viewports.rst
Summary: This section explains how to render content to a SubViewport and display it using a ViewportTexture, covering texture clearing and update modes.

When rendering to a SubViewport, its contents are not visible in the scene editor. To display these contents, you must draw the SubViewport's ViewportTexture somewhere. This can be done via code:

GDScript:
    # This gives us the ViewportTexture.
    var tex = viewport.get_texture()
    sprite.texture = tex

C#:
    // This gives us the ViewportTexture.
    var tex = viewport.GetTexture();
    sprite.Texture = tex;

Alternatively, in the editor, you can assign a "New ViewportTexture" and select the desired Viewport.

Each frame, the Viewport's texture is cleared with the default clear color, or a transparent color if Transparent BG is set to true. This clearing behavior can be modified by setting the Render Target Clear Mode to Never or Next Frame. "Never" prevents the texture from being cleared, while "Next Frame" clears it on the subsequent frame and then reverts to "Never".

By default, a SubViewport re-renders only when its ViewportTexture has been drawn in a frame. If it's visible, it renders; otherwise, it does not. This can be altered by setting the Render Target Update Mode to Never, Once, Always, or When Parent Visible. "Never" and "Always" will prevent or force re-rendering, respectively. "Once" will re-render the next frame and then switch to "Never", enabling manual updates. This provides flexibility to render an image once and reuse the texture without the overhead of per-frame rendering.

Note: The Viewport demos are available in the viewport folder of the demos archive or on GitHub.